ebruary 1499":"13. února 1499","1516":"1516","1515":"1515","1504":"1504","Bradgate Park, Leicestershire, England":"Bradgate Park, Leicestershire, Anglie","Sidmouth, Devon, England":"Sidmouth, Devon, Anglie","Isle of Man":"Ostrov Man","Upholland, Lancashire, England":"Up Holland, Lancashire, Anglie"},"da":{"13 February 1499–1516":"13. februar 1499–1516","1499–1516":"1499–1516","1485–1563":"1485–1563","1515–1567":"1515–1567","1469–1502":"1469–1502","1502":"1502","1469":"1469","1567":"1567","31 August 1502":"31. august 1502","1499":"1499","1563":"1563","1485":"1485","13 February 1499":"13. februar 1499","1516":"1516","1515":"1515","1504":"1504","Bradgate Park, Leicestershire, England":"Bradgate Park, Leicestershire, England","Sidmouth, Devon, England":"Sidmouth, Devon, England","Isle of Man":"Isle of Man","Upholland, Lancashire, England":"Up Holland, Lancashire, England"},"nl":{"13 February 1499–1516":"13 februari 1499–1516","1499–1516":"1499–1516","1485–1563":"1485–1563","1515–1567":"1515–1567","1469–1502":"1469–1502","1502":"1502","1469":"1469","1567":"1567","31 August 1502":"31 augustus 1502","1499":"1499","1563":"1563","1485":"1485","13 February 1499":"13 februari 1499","1516":"1516","1515":"1515","1504":"1504","Bradgate Park, Leicestershire, England":"Bradgate Park, Leicestershire, England","Sidmouth, Devon, England":"Sidmouth, Devon, England","Isle of Man":"Man","Upholland, Lancashire, England":"Up Holland, Lancashire, England"},"en":{"13 February 1499–1516":"13 February 1499–1516","1499–1516":"1499–1516","1485–1563":"1485–1563","1515–1567":"1515–1567","1469–1502":"1469–1502","1502":"1502","1469":"1469","1567":"1567","31 August 1502":"31 August 1502","1499":"1499","1563":"1563","1485":"1485","13 February 1499":"13 February 1499","1516":"1516","1515":"1515","1504":"1504","Bradgate Park, Leicestershire, England":"Bradgate Park, Leicestershire, England","Sidmouth, Devon, England":"Sidmouth, Devon, England","Isle of Man":"Isle of Man","Upholland, Lancashire, England":"Up Holland, Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Holland","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, German, Dutch, Danish, Norwegian, Swedish, French, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name from <i>Holland</i>, a province of the Netherlands.","English: habitational name from Downholland or Upholland (Lancashire), Hulland (Derbyshire), the Parts of Holland, one of the three administrative subdivisions of Lincolnshire, any of the four places called Hoyland (southern Yorkshire), and possibly Great and Little Holland (Essex). The placenames all derive from Old English <i>hōh</i> ‘heel, spur of land’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’.","English: habitational name either from Hoeland (Farm) in Bury (Sussex), or from Holland's Barn in Albourne (Sussex). The placename in Bury has the same etymology as in 1 above, while the placename in Albourne may derive from Old English <i>hol</i> ‘hole, hollow’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’."],"variants":[{"name":"Hollands","meanings":["English: variant of   Holland  , especially 3, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Dutch: genitivized form of   Holland  ."]},{"name":"Howland","meanings":["English: variant of   Holland  .","Americanized form of Norwegian   Hovland  .","History: Howland was the name of three Quaker brothers, original settlers in Marshfield, MA. They were from Huntingdonshire, England. The eldest, John Howland (<i>c.</i> 1593–1672) was a passenger on the <i>Mayflower</i>, servant to Gov. John Carver, who died in the first winter at Plymouth Colony."]},{"name":"Hollander","meanings":["Dutch (also <b>Den Hollander</b>), German (also <b>Holländer</b>), English, Swedish, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name for someone from Holland (see   Holland   1)."]},{"name":"Holand","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Holland  .","Norwegian: habitational name from about twenty farmsteads so named, composed of Old Norse <i>hár</i> ‘high’ + <i>land</i> ‘land, field’, denoting a high-lying farm."]},{"name":"Aland","meanings":["Scandinavian (<b>Åland</b>): topographic name from the Åland Islands in the Gulf of Bothnia.","English: topographic name from Middle English <i>atte lande</i> (Old French <i>laund</i>) ‘dweller at the glade or pasture’, or sometimes perhaps, ‘dweller at the old cultivated land(s)’ from Old English <i>eald</i>, <i>ald</i> ‘old’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’."]},{"name":"Hollon","meanings":["English: altered form of   Holland  ."]}]},{"name":"Myrtle","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the vocabulary word denoting the plant (Old French <i>myrtille</i>, Late Latin <i>myrtilla</i>, a diminutive of classical Latin <i>myrta</i>). This is one of the group of plant names that became popular as girls' names in the late 19th century. It has since gone out of fashion."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Grace","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the abstract noun (via Old French, from Latin <i>gratia</i>), this name occurs occasionally in the 15th century, and by the 1540s was among the most popular girls' names in some parishes. It has always been particularly popular in Scotland and northern England (borne, for example, by  Grace Darling , the lighthouse keeper's daughter whose heroism in  1838 , saving sailors in a storm, caught the popular imagination). In more recent times it was famous as the name of the actress  Grace Kelly  (  1928–82 ), who became  Princess Grace  of Monaco. In Ireland it is used as an Anglicized form of   Gráinne   ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1354214,"age":4,"year":"1504","julianDay":2270384,"description":"Title King of Man waived for Lord of Mann.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Myrtle Grace Holland was born on 13 February 1499, in Up Holland, Lancashire, England as the daughter of Thoma